<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25181h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25181h">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25181h"> 181(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 4 chapters of / coming forth / by night <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n25181h"><li>FW 62.27 </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/lexc.htm#n25181h">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/l39c.htm#n25181h">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n25181h">MS BL 47472-152</ms> </li><li>JJA 46:191 <a name="c3d" href="../../ff/fdra/cda.htm#c3d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/c/c3d.htm#n25181h">Draft: I.3&sect;1.3</a>/2.3/3.3</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The famous collections of ancient texts, from sarcophagi of early date, to which the name <cite>Peri-em-hru</cite> (or &ldquo;<mark>going forth from day</mark>&rdquo;) was given&mdash;now known as the Book, or Ritual, of the Dead&mdash;consist, indeed, of nothing but charms of the most primitive description, whereby the soul was fortified against its demon foes, appearing as snakes or crocodiles in Hades, and passed the pits of flame, and the closed gates of various regions, to reach the judgment hall of Osiris, where the heart was weighed before the Council of the gods. <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 164</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The full title for the collection of Ancient Egyptian writings now called <cite>The Book of the Dead</cite> was &ldquo;The chapters of going forth by day and by night &hellip; to the place he might desire to be.&rdquo; See also: <a name="n25117h" href="n25all.htm#n25117h">N25 (VI.B.15):117(h)</a> and <a name="n25158l" href="n25all.htm#n25158l">N25 (VI.B.15):158(l)</a></mm> </dd></dl>
